// Jest Snapshot v1, https://goo.gl/fbAQLP

exports[`loadFormExamples snapshot matches the expected full output snapshot 1`] = `
"# Best Practices

## Layout Selection
Choose the right root layout based on form complexity
- **Simple forms (1-5 fields, single purpose)**: Use VerticalLayout as root
- **Complex forms (6+ fields, multiple sections)**: Use Categorization with variant="pages"

## Validation Checklist
Pre-save validation checklist
- All UI schema scopes reference properties that exist in the data schema
- Required fields in data schema are clearly marked in the \`required\` array
- Property names use camelCase convention
- Each Control has a valid scope starting with \`#/properties/\`
- No orphaned required fields (every required field has a matching property)
- Data schema \`type\` is \`"object"\` at the root level

## Accessibility
- Include descriptive labels — property names are auto-converted to labels but may need refinement
- Add inline help for complex fields using \`options.help\`
- Use HelpContent elements for important notices, privacy statements, or instructions
- Provide clear error messages in validation rules
- Keep help text at grade 9 reading level for citizen-facing forms

## Common Fields
Use ADSP common schema definitions instead of building fields from scratch
- **Full Name**: \`https://adsp.alberta.ca/common.v1.schema.json#/definitions/personFullName\` — First name, middle name, and last name input fields
- **Address**: \`https://adsp.alberta.ca/common.v1.schema.json#/definitions/postalAddressAlberta\` — Structured postal address (addressLine1, municipality, subdivisionCode, postalCode)
Usage: Use schemaDefinitionTool to load definitions, then reference them with $ref in data schema properties

## Iterative Workflow
1. Load existing form configuration with formConfigurationRetrievalTool
2. Ask for the purpose of the form if unclear
3. Start with 1-3 fields and apply via formConfigurationUpdateTool
4. Ask for user feedback after each update
5. Add more fields, refine layouts, and add help text incrementally
6. Don't dump JSON — describe changes and use the update tool

# UI Control Examples

## Text Area
Multi-line text input using the \`multi\` option on a string Control

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "message": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/message",
  "options": {
    "multi": true
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Set \`options.multi\` to \`true\` on any Control bound to a string property
- The textarea will grow based on content by default

## Inline Help Content
Add contextual help text to a form control using \`options.help\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/firstName",
  "options": {
    "help": "Please enter your first name as it appears on your official documents."
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Keep help text concise and actionable
- Use plain language — aim for grade 9 reading level
- Help text appears below the input field

## File Upload
File upload control using \`file-urn\` format on a string property

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "photo": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "file-urn"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/photo"
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- The \`format: "file-urn"\` on the data schema property enables the file upload control
- No special UI schema options are needed — just a Control bound to the property
- Uploaded files are stored via the ADSP File Service and referenced by URN

## Date Input
Date picker control using the \`date\` format on a string property

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "dateOfBirth": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "date"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/dateOfBirth"
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use \`format: "date"\` in the data schema — the renderer automatically provides a date picker
- The value is stored in ISO 8601 format (YYYY-MM-DD)
- No special UI schema options are needed; just a Control pointing to the property

## Integer Input with Min/Max
Numeric integer input with min, max, and step using \`componentProps\`

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "numberOfChildren": {
      "type": "integer"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/numberOfChildren",
  "options": {
    "componentProps": {
      "min": 0,
      "max": 20,
      "step": 1
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use \`type: "integer"\` in data schema for whole numbers, \`type: "number"\` for decimals
- Use \`options.componentProps\` to pass min, max, and step to the underlying Design System component
- componentProps are passed directly to the GoA Design System input component

## Boolean Yes/No Radio
Boolean field rendered as Yes/No radio buttons using \`format: radio\` option

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "isOver18": {
      "type": "boolean"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/isOver18",
  "label": "Are you over 18 years of age?",
  "options": {
    "format": "radio",
    "textForTrue": "Yes",
    "textForFalse": "No"
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Set \`options.format\` to \`"radio"\` to render as radio buttons
- Use \`textForTrue\` and \`textForFalse\` to customize the labels (defaults to 'Yes'/'No')
- The \`label\` property overrides the auto-generated label from the property name
- Boolean radios are ideal for triggering rules that SHOW/HIDE dependent fields

## Dropdown Select
Dropdown menu for selecting from a predefined list using \`enum\` in the data schema

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "province": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "Alberta",
        "British Columbia",
        "Saskatchewan",
        "Manitoba",
        "Ontario",
        "Quebec"
      ]
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/province",
  "label": "Select your province"
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Define the options in \`enum\` array on the data schema property — renders as a dropdown by default
- For 3 or fewer options, consider using radio buttons instead for better UX
- The label on the UI schema overrides the auto-generated label from the property name
- For dynamic lists loaded from an API or configuration, use data registers instead of enum

## Radio Buttons
Radio button group using \`enum\` in data schema and \`format: radio\` in UI schema

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "preferredContact": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "email",
        "phone",
        "mail"
      ]
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/preferredContact",
  "label": "Preferred contact method",
  "options": {
    "format": "radio",
    "componentProps": {
      "orientation": "horizontal"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Set \`options.format\` to \`"radio"\` to render enum values as radio buttons instead of dropdown
- Use \`componentProps.orientation\` to control layout: \`"horizontal"\` or \`"vertical"\`
- Radio buttons are best for 2-4 options; use dropdowns for longer lists

## Required Declaration Checkbox
Required checkbox that must be checked to submit, using \`allOf\` with \`enum: [true]\` validation

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "iDeclare": {
      "type": "boolean",
      "allOf": [
        {
          "enum": [
            true
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "iDeclare"
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/iDeclare",
  "options": {
    "text": "I declare the information provided is correct to the best of my knowledge"
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- The \`allOf: [{ enum: [true] }]\` pattern forces the checkbox to be checked (not just present)
- Without \`allOf\`, a \`required\` boolean would accept both true and false as valid
- Use \`options.text\` to set the checkbox label text
- This pattern is essential for FOIP consent and declaration checkboxes on government forms

## Required String Field (minLength Workaround)
Required text field with \`minLength: 1\` workaround for the known JSON Forms empty-string bug

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "firstName": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "firstName"
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/firstName"
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- CRITICAL: There is a known JSON Forms bug where an empty string satisfies the \`required\` rule
- Always add \`minLength: 1\` to required string fields as a workaround
- Without \`minLength: 1\`, users can submit the form with blank required fields
- This applies to ALL required string fields — text inputs, text areas, emails, etc.

## File Upload (Drag & Drop)
Drag and drop file upload variant using \`file-urn\` format and \`variant: dragdrop\`

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "certificateOfOwnership": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "file-urn"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/certificateOfOwnership",
  "options": {
    "variant": "dragdrop"
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Set \`variant: "dragdrop"\` in UI schema options for the drag-and-drop upload area
- The default variant is \`"button"\` which renders a 'Choose file' button
- Also set the \`variant\` property on the data schema for the upload style: \`"button"\` (default) or \`"dragdrop"\`
- Uploaded files are stored in Azure Blob storage via the ADSP File Service
- The field value becomes a file URN like \`urn:ads:platform:file-service:v1:/files/<uuid>\`

# Layout Examples

## Multi-Page Form Layout
Categorization with \`variant: pages\` to create a step-by-step multi-page form

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "firstName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "lastName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "email": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "email"
    },
    "phoneNumber": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Categorization",
  "options": {
    "variant": "pages"
  },
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Category",
      "label": "Personal Information",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/firstName"
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/lastName"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Category",
      "label": "Contact Information",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/email"
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/phoneNumber"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use Categorization with \`variant: "pages"\` as the root UI schema element
- Each Category becomes a separate page/step in the form
- Give each Category a descriptive \`label\` — this is shown as the page title
- Group related fields into the same Category

## Simple Vertical Layout
VerticalLayout for simple single-page forms with a few fields

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "name": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "email": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "email"
    },
    "message": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "name",
    "email"
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/name"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/email"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/message",
      "options": {
        "multi": true
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use VerticalLayout as the root when the form is simple and single-purpose
- Fields render top-to-bottom in the order listed in elements
- Combine with \`required\` in the data schema to mark mandatory fields

## Horizontal Layout (Side by Side)
HorizontalLayout to render fields side by side in a row

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "firstName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "lastName": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "HorizontalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/firstName"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/lastName"
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- HorizontalLayout places elements side by side in a single row
- Each element gets equal width by default
- On narrow screens, elements may stack vertically depending on the renderer
- Best for 2-3 related short fields; avoid more than 3 to prevent crowding

## Mixed Nested Layout
VerticalLayout containing a HorizontalLayout to mix row and column arrangements

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "firstName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "lastName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "reasonForLeaving": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "HorizontalLayout",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/firstName"
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/lastName"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/reasonForLeaving",
      "options": {
        "multi": true
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Nest a HorizontalLayout inside a VerticalLayout to create mixed arrangements
- This is the most common layout pattern for forms with name fields + longer inputs
- Layouts can be nested up to several levels deep, but keep it simple for readability

## Group Layout with Label
Group element that wraps controls in a labeled section (like a VerticalLayout with a heading)

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "firstName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "lastName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "initial": {
      "type": "string",
      "maxLength": 1
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Group",
  "label": "Personal Information",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/firstName"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/lastName"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/initial"
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- A Group is like a VerticalLayout but with a visible label/heading
- The \`label\` property sets the section heading text
- Groups render with visual separation (border/card) depending on the renderer
- Use Groups within pages/categories to sub-divide long sections

## Page Stepper with Section Titles
Multi-page form using Categorization with \`variant: pages\`, section titles, and nested object scopes

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "name": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "firstName": {
          "type": "string",
          "minLength": 2
        },
        "lastName": {
          "type": "string",
          "minLength": 2
        },
        "initial": {
          "type": "string",
          "maxLength": 1
        }
      }
    },
    "address": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "street": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "city": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Categorization",
  "options": {
    "variant": "pages",
    "title": "Application Form",
    "subtitle": "Tell us about yourself"
  },
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Category",
      "label": "Name",
      "options": {
        "sectionTitle": "Identification"
      },
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "VerticalLayout",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/name/properties/firstName"
            },
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/name/properties/lastName"
            },
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/name/properties/initial"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Category",
      "label": "Address",
      "options": {
        "sectionTitle": "Residence"
      },
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "VerticalLayout",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/address/properties/street"
            },
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/address/properties/city"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use \`options.variant: "pages"\` for the Design System's preferred page stepper pattern
- Use \`options.variant: "stepper"\` for the simple stepper (navigation bar at top)
- Each Category becomes a page; \`sectionTitle\` groups categories into sections on the task list
- For nested objects, scopes must use the full path: \`#/properties/name/properties/firstName\`
- A Summary page is automatically appended by the GoA renderer for applicant review
- Use \`options.title\` and \`options.subtitle\` on Categorization for the task list header

# Common Field Examples

## Full Name (Common Field)
Reusable full name field using the ADSP common schema $ref definition for person name

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "yourFullNameProperty": {
      "$ref": "https://adsp.alberta.ca/common.v1.schema.json#/definitions/personFullName"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/yourFullNameProperty"
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use the schemaDefinitionTool to load the common schema definitions first
- The definition is \`personFullName\` — not \`fullName\`
- Reference definitions with \`$ref\` — this renders firstName, middleName, lastName subfields
- Replace \`yourFullNameProperty\` with a meaningful property name like \`applicantName\`
- For name + date of birth together, use \`personFullNameAndDob\` instead

## Address (Common Field)
Reusable address field using the ADSP common schema $ref definition for postal address

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "yourAddressProperty": {
      "$ref": "https://adsp.alberta.ca/common.v1.schema.json#/definitions/postalAddressAlberta"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/yourAddressProperty"
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use the schemaDefinitionTool to load the common schema definitions first
- The definition is \`postalAddressAlberta\` (for AB-only) or \`postalAddressCanada\` (all provinces)
- Reference definitions with \`$ref\` — this renders structured address subfields automatically
- Replace \`yourAddressProperty\` with a meaningful property name like \`mailingAddress\`
- Subfields: addressLine1, addressLine2, municipality, subdivisionCode, postalCode, country

# Content Element Examples

## Help Content Block
Descriptive help or notice block using HelpContent element with markdown support

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "HelpContent",
  "options": {
    "markdown": true,
    "help": [
      "#### Notice of Collection:",
      "The personal information on this form is collected under the authority of Section 33(c) of the Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act (FOIP) and will be used for the purpose of administering the Alberta Approved Farmers' Market Program. If you have any questions about the collection and use of your information, please contact the Farmers' Market Specialist, Alberta Agriculture, Forestry and Rural Development at [ab.approvedfarmersmarket@gov.ab.ca](ab.approvedfarmersmarket@gov.ab.ca) or telephone: 780-581-4107."
    ]
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Set \`options.markdown\` to \`true\` to enable markdown rendering
- Use an array for \`options.help\` to separate content into multiple lines/paragraphs
- HelpContent does not have a scope — it's a display-only element, not bound to data
- Useful for FOIP/privacy notices required on Alberta government forms

## Markdown Help Content
Rich HelpContent using markdown for formatted text, links, images, and bullet points. This is the recommended way to add links and images in forms.

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "HelpContent",
  "label": "Program Overview",
  "options": {
    "markdown": true,
    "help": [
      "## Section Heading",
      "This is a paragraph with some **bold** text and _italic_ text.",
      "Visit [Alberta.ca](https://alberta.ca) for more information.",
      "![Application process diagram](https://example.com/diagram.png)",
      "- First bullet point",
      "- Second bullet point",
      "- Third bullet point",
      "See the [Alberta Privacy Policy](https://www.alberta.ca/privacy-policy) for details."
    ]
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Set \`options.markdown\` to \`true\` to enable markdown rendering
- The \`help\` array contains one paragraph per entry — each entry can use markdown syntax
- Supports headings (##), bold (**), italic (_), links ([text](url)), images (![alt](url)), and bullet lists (-)
- For hyperlinks use \`[link text](url)\` — this replaces the deprecated \`variant: hyperlink\`
- For images use \`![alt text](url)\` — this replaces the deprecated \`variant: img\`
- Extended markdown syntax (tables, footnotes) is NOT currently supported

## Collapsible Details Section
HelpContent with \`variant: details\` to create a click-to-expand section for long instructions

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "HelpContent",
  "label": "How to calculate your household income",
  "options": {
    "variant": "details",
    "help": "Household income is based on line 15000 (gross income) minus applicable amounts."
  },
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "HelpContent",
      "options": {
        "help": [
          "Line 21000 (deduction for split-pension amount)",
          "Line 32000 (tuition expenses)",
          "Line 33099 (medical expenses for self, spouse or common-law partner)",
          "Line 33199 (medical expenses for other dependants)"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Set \`options.variant\` to \`"details"\` to make the section collapsible
- The \`label\` becomes the clickable title that expands/collapses the details
- Nested \`elements\` contain the detail content revealed when expanded
- Array in \`help\` renders as a bulleted list; string renders as a paragraph
- This keeps forms clean while preserving access to reference information

## Markdown Link in Form
Add clickable hyperlinks inside a form using markdown HelpContent with \`[text](url)\` syntax

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "HelpContent",
  "options": {
    "markdown": true,
    "help": [
      "Please review the [Alberta Privacy Policy](https://www.alberta.ca/privacy-policy) before submitting.",
      "For more details, visit [Alberta.ca](https://www.alberta.ca)."
    ]
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use standard markdown link syntax: \`[link text](url)\`
- Set \`options.markdown\` to \`true\` to enable markdown rendering
- Multiple links can appear in the same help entry or across entries
- Links open in a new tab by default
- The old \`variant: hyperlink\` approach is deprecated — always use markdown links

## Markdown Image in Form
Display an image inside a form using markdown HelpContent with \`![alt](url)\` syntax

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "HelpContent",
  "options": {
    "markdown": true,
    "help": [
      "![Application process diagram](https://example.com/diagram.png)",
      "The diagram above shows the steps in the application process."
    ]
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use standard markdown image syntax: \`![alt text](image-url)\`
- Set \`options.markdown\` to \`true\` to enable markdown rendering
- Always provide descriptive alt text for screen reader accessibility
- The image URL must be a fully qualified public URL
- The old \`variant: img\` approach is deprecated — always use markdown images

# Repeating Items Examples

## List with Detail (Repeating Items)
ListWithDetail for collecting a variable number of complex items with full layout control

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "familyMembers": {
      "type": "array",
      "items": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "firstName": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "lastName": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "relationship": {
            "type": "string",
            "enum": [
              "Spouse",
              "Child",
              "Parent",
              "Sibling"
            ]
          },
          "dateOfBirth": {
            "type": "string",
            "format": "date"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "ListWithDetail",
  "scope": "#/properties/familyMembers",
  "options": {
    "detail": {
      "type": "VerticalLayout",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "HorizontalLayout",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/firstName",
              "label": "First Name"
            },
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/lastName",
              "label": "Last Name"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/relationship"
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/dateOfBirth"
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- ListWithDetail shows a list panel on the left and detail form on the right
- The \`detail\` object in options defines the layout for each item — you have full layout control
- Scopes inside \`detail\` are relative to the array item, NOT the root: use \`#/properties/firstName\` not \`#/properties/familyMembers/items/properties/firstName\`
- Use \`items.type: "object"\` in the data schema to define the shape of each list entry
- Users can add/remove items dynamically; the list displays item count

## Object Array (Simple Repeating Items)
Simple repeating items using a Control bound to an array property — auto-generated layout

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "people": {
      "type": "array",
      "items": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "firstName": {
            "type": "string"
          },
          "lastName": {
            "type": "string"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "label": "People",
  "scope": "#/properties/people"
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- The simplest way to add repeating items — just point a Control at an array property
- Each item renders as a card with auto-generated layout for its properties
- You lose control over how item fields are arranged (no custom layout)
- Best for small lists with simple items; use ListWithDetail for complex items
- Each property on an item renders as a separate row on the card

# Rule Examples

## Show/Hide Rule (Conditional Visibility)
SHOW or HIDE form elements based on boolean, string, or other field values using JSON Forms rules

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "hasChildren": {
      "type": "boolean"
    },
    "numberOfChildren": {
      "type": "integer"
    },
    "childsFirstName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "childsLastName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "needsAccommodation": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "yes",
        "no"
      ]
    },
    "accommodationDetails": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "termsAccepted": {
      "type": "boolean"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/hasChildren",
      "label": "Do you have children?"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/numberOfChildren",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/hasChildren",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/childsFirstName",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/hasChildren",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/childsLastName",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/hasChildren",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/needsAccommodation",
      "label": "Do you need an accommodation?",
      "options": {
        "componentProps": {
          "name": "needsAccommodation"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/accommodationDetails",
      "label": "Please describe the accommodation needed",
      "options": {
        "multi": true
      },
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/needsAccommodation",
          "schema": {
            "const": "yes"
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/termsAccepted",
      "label": "I accept the terms and conditions"
    },
    {
      "type": "HelpContent",
      "label": "",
      "options": {
        "help": "⚠ You must accept the terms and conditions before submitting.",
        "variant": "important"
      },
      "rule": {
        "effect": "HIDE",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/termsAccepted",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Attach a \`rule\` object to any UI schema element (Control, Layout, Group, etc.)
- The \`effect\` can be \`SHOW\`, \`HIDE\`, \`ENABLE\`, or \`DISABLE\`
- SHOW: element is hidden by default, shown when condition is TRUE
- HIDE: element is visible by default, hidden when condition is TRUE — the INVERSE of SHOW
- The \`condition.scope\` points to the field being evaluated; \`condition.schema\` is a JSON schema to match
- Use \`const\` for exact value matching (boolean, string, number): \`{ const: true }\`, \`{ const: "yes" }\`, \`{ const: 42 }\`
- String matching: \`{ const: "yes" }\` matches exactly 'yes'; \`{ enum: ["yes", "maybe"] }\` matches either value
- IMPORTANT: Hidden fields can still be \`required\` — use conditional validation (if/then) to avoid validation errors on hidden fields
- A rule can be attached to a layout element to show/hide an entire group of fields at once
- Choose SHOW vs HIDE based on default state: use SHOW when hidden-by-default, HIDE when visible-by-default

## Enable/Disable Rule
ENABLE or DISABLE a field based on another field's value — field remains visible but read-only when disabled

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "isDead": {
      "type": "boolean"
    },
    "kindOfDead": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "hasLicense": {
      "type": "boolean"
    },
    "licenseNumber": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "licenseExpiry": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "date"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/isDead",
      "label": "Is Dead?"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/kindOfDead",
      "label": "Kind of dead",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "ENABLE",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/isDead",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/hasLicense",
      "label": "Do you have a licence?"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/licenseNumber",
      "label": "Licence Number",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "ENABLE",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/hasLicense",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/licenseExpiry",
      "label": "Licence Expiry Date",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "ENABLE",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/hasLicense",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- ENABLE: field starts disabled, becomes enabled when condition is TRUE
- DISABLE: field starts enabled, becomes disabled when condition is TRUE — the INVERSE of ENABLE
- Use ENABLE/DISABLE when you want the field to remain visible but toggled between editable and read-only
- Disabled fields display their current value but don't accept input
- Unlike SHOW/HIDE, the field is always visible — use this for fields that provide context
- Choose ENABLE vs DISABLE based on the default state: use ENABLE when disabled-by-default, DISABLE when enabled-by-default
- You can combine ENABLE/DISABLE with conditional required validation (if/then) to make a field required only when it is enabled

## Rule with Enum / Multi-Value Matching
Show or hide elements based on matching one of several values using \`enum\` in the rule condition

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "memberType": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "employee",
        "contractor",
        "volunteer",
        "other"
      ]
    },
    "employeeId": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "contractorCompany": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "volunteerOrganization": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/memberType",
      "label": "What is your role?"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/employeeId",
      "label": "Employee ID",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/memberType",
          "schema": {
            "const": "employee"
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/contractorCompany",
      "label": "Contractor Company",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/memberType",
          "schema": {
            "enum": [
              "contractor",
              "other"
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/volunteerOrganization",
      "label": "Volunteer Organization",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/memberType",
          "schema": {
            "const": "volunteer"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use \`const\` in condition schema to match a single value exactly
- Use \`enum\` in condition schema to match any of several values
- Use \`not: { const: value }\` to negate — show when value is NOT a specific value
- Numeric ranges: use \`minimum\`, \`maximum\`, \`exclusiveMinimum\`, \`exclusiveMaximum\`
- You can scope the condition to \`#\` (root) and use a full JSON schema for complex multi-property conditions

## Multi-Criteria Rule (AND / OR Logic)
Show, hide, enable, or disable an element based on multiple field values using \`scope: "#"\` with a full JSON Schema condition

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "employmentStatus": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "employed",
        "self-employed",
        "unemployed",
        "retired"
      ]
    },
    "province": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "Alberta",
        "British Columbia",
        "Ontario",
        "Other"
      ]
    },
    "annualIncome": {
      "type": "number"
    },
    "albertaEmployeeBenefitInfo": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "retirementPlanDetails": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/employmentStatus",
      "label": "Employment Status"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/province",
      "label": "Province"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/annualIncome",
      "label": "Annual Income ($)"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/albertaEmployeeBenefitInfo",
      "label": "Alberta Employee Benefit Details",
      "options": {
        "help": "This field only appears when you are employed AND in Alberta."
      },
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#",
          "schema": {
            "properties": {
              "employmentStatus": {
                "const": "employed"
              },
              "province": {
                "const": "Alberta"
              }
            },
            "required": [
              "employmentStatus",
              "province"
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/retirementPlanDetails",
      "label": "Retirement Plan Details",
      "options": {
        "help": "This field appears when you are retired OR self-employed."
      },
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#",
          "schema": {
            "anyOf": [
              {
                "properties": {
                  "employmentStatus": {
                    "const": "retired"
                  }
                },
                "required": [
                  "employmentStatus"
                ]
              },
              {
                "properties": {
                  "employmentStatus": {
                    "const": "self-employed"
                  }
                },
                "required": [
                  "employmentStatus"
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- For AND logic: set \`condition.scope\` to \`"#"\` (root) and provide a JSON Schema with multiple \`properties\` and \`required\`
- All listed properties must match for the condition to be true — this is AND logic
- For OR logic: use \`anyOf\` inside the condition schema — the condition is true if ANY sub-schema matches
- IMPORTANT: Include \`required\` in the condition schema to ensure fields must be present for the condition to match
- You can combine AND and OR: \`{ properties: { a: ... }, required: [...], anyOf: [...] }\`
- This works with all effects: SHOW, HIDE, ENABLE, DISABLE
- For negation (NOT): wrap in \`not: { properties: { ... }, required: [...] }\` inside the condition schema
- The single-field \`condition.scope: "#/properties/fieldName"\` pattern only checks ONE field — use \`scope: "#"\` for multi-field conditions

## Rule on Group Wrapper (Multi-Element Rule)
Attach a rule to a Group or VerticalLayout to show/hide multiple elements at once. Includes wrap and unwrap procedures.

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "hasSpouse": {
      "type": "boolean"
    },
    "spouseFirstName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "spouseLastName": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "spouseEmail": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "email"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/hasSpouse",
      "label": "Do you have a spouse?"
    },
    {
      "type": "Group",
      "label": "Spouse Information",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/hasSpouse",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      },
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/spouseFirstName",
          "label": "Spouse First Name"
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/spouseLastName",
          "label": "Spouse Last Name"
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/spouseEmail",
          "label": "Spouse Email"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- A \`rule\` can be attached to ANY UI schema element: Control, Group, VerticalLayout, HorizontalLayout, Category, etc.
- When a rule is on a layout/Group, ALL child elements are shown/hidden/enabled/disabled together
- 
- ## WRAP PROCEDURE — Adding an element to an existing single-element rule:
- 1. Create a new Group or VerticalLayout element
- 2. Move the existing element (with its rule) inside as a child
- 3. Add the new element as another child
- 4. Move the \`rule\` from the original element UP to the new wrapper
- 5. Remove the \`rule\` from the original element (now the wrapper controls visibility)
- 
- ## UNWRAP PROCEDURE — Removing an element from a multi-element rule:
- 1. Remove the element from the wrapper's \`elements\` array
- 2. Place the removed element where it should go (e.g., outside the wrapper, or in another section)
- 3. If only ONE element remains in the wrapper, move the \`rule\` down to that element and delete the wrapper
- 4. If zero elements remain, delete the wrapper entirely
- 
- ## ADD CRITERIA PROCEDURE — Adding a condition to an existing rule:
- 1. If the rule currently uses \`scope: "#/properties/field"\`, change it to \`scope: "#"\` and restructure the condition as a full JSON Schema
- 2. Add the new property check to the \`properties\` and \`required\` in the condition schema
- 3. For OR logic, wrap existing and new conditions in \`anyOf\`
- 
- ## REMOVE CRITERIA PROCEDURE — Removing a condition from a rule:
- 1. Remove the property from the condition schema's \`properties\` and \`required\`
- 2. If only one property remains AND the condition used \`scope: "#"\`, simplify back to \`scope: "#/properties/field"\` with \`schema: { const: value }\`
- 3. If removing from \`anyOf\`, remove the sub-schema entry; if only one remains, unwrap it from the \`anyOf\` array

# Validation Examples

## Conditional Required (if/then)
Conditionally required fields using JSON Schema if/then/else — essential when using SHOW/HIDE rules

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "hasChildren": {
      "type": "boolean"
    },
    "childsFirstName": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1
    },
    "childsLastName": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "hasChildren"
  ],
  "if": {
    "properties": {
      "hasChildren": {
        "const": true
      }
    }
  },
  "then": {
    "required": [
      "childsFirstName",
      "childsLastName"
    ]
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/hasChildren",
      "label": "Do you have children?"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/childsFirstName",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/hasChildren",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/childsLastName",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/hasChildren",
          "schema": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- CRITICAL: Always pair SHOW/HIDE rules with conditional validation in the data schema
- Without if/then, hidden required fields cause form validation to fail silently
- The \`if/then\` construct is at the top level of the data schema (same level as \`properties\` and \`required\`)
- Add \`minLength: 1\` to conditionally required string fields for the empty-string workaround
- There can only be one \`if/then\` at each schema level — use \`allOf\` for multiple conditions

## Multiple Conditional Validations (allOf)
Multiple if/then blocks wrapped in \`allOf\` for forms with several conditional required fields

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "hasChildren": {
      "type": "boolean"
    },
    "childsFirstName": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1
    },
    "childsLastName": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1
    },
    "category": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "General Inquiry",
        "Highway Issues",
        "Environmental Concern"
      ]
    },
    "highwayIssueDetails": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "category"
  ],
  "allOf": [
    {
      "if": {
        "properties": {
          "hasChildren": {
            "const": true
          }
        }
      },
      "then": {
        "required": [
          "childsFirstName",
          "childsLastName"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "if": {
        "properties": {
          "category": {
            "const": "Highway Issues"
          }
        }
      },
      "then": {
        "required": [
          "highwayIssueDetails"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Wrap multiple if/then blocks in \`allOf\` at the root level of the data schema
- You can add as many conditional validation blocks as needed inside \`allOf\`
- Each \`if/then\` is independent — they don't interfere with each other
- You can conditionally specify ANY JSON Schema validation: required, pattern, minLength, format, etc.
- Be sure to pair each conditional validation with a matching SHOW/HIDE rule in the UI schema

## Custom Error Messages
Override default AJV validation error messages with user-friendly text using \`errorMessage\` in schema

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "firstName": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 2,
      "maxLength": 15,
      "pattern": "^[a-zA-Z]*$",
      "errorMessage": {
        "pattern": "First name must only contain letters.",
        "minLength": "Minimum length for first name is 2 characters.",
        "maxLength": "Maximum length for first name is 15 characters."
      }
    },
    "email": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "email",
      "errorMessage": {
        "_": "Please enter a valid email address."
      }
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/firstName"
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/email"
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Add \`errorMessage\` object to any property in the data schema
- Map each constraint keyword (pattern, minLength, maxLength, format) to a custom error string
- Use \`"_"\` as the key for a default message that applies to ALL constraints on that field
- If a constraint is omitted from errorMessage, the default AJV error is used
- The \`required\` field validation message is NOT customizable — it always shows '{fieldName} is required'
- Keep error messages at grade 9 reading level for citizen-facing government forms

# Data Register Examples

## Data Register — Configuration Service
Populate a dropdown with dynamic data from the ADSP Configuration Service using a URN register

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "provinces": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        ""
      ]
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/provinces",
  "label": "Province",
  "options": {
    "register": {
      "urn": "urn:ads:platform:configuration:v2:/configuration/public-register/public-register-1"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Set \`enum: [""]\` as a placeholder in the data schema — the actual values are loaded from the register
- The \`options.register.urn\` points to a Configuration Service configuration definition
- Admin-managed lists can be updated without changing the form definition
- The register data can be an array of strings or array of \`{label, value}\` objects
- Requires the JsonFormRegisterProvider context wrapper in the React integration

## Data Register — External API Endpoint
Populate a dropdown with data from an external REST API using a URL register

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "carBrand": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        ""
      ]
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Control",
  "scope": "#/properties/carBrand",
  "label": "Select car brand",
  "options": {
    "register": {
      "url": "https://parallelum.com.br/fipe/api/v1/carros/marcas",
      "objectPathInArray": "nome"
    }
  }
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- Use \`options.register.url\` for external REST API endpoints that return JSON arrays
- The \`objectPathInArray\` property specifies which JSON property to use as the dropdown label and value
- For example, if the API returns \`[{"codigo": "1", "nome": "Acura"}]\`, use \`objectPathInArray: "nome"\`
- Set \`enum: [""]\` as a placeholder in the data schema — the actual values are loaded from the API
- Requires the JsonFormRegisterProvider context wrapper in the React integration

# Complex Scenario Examples

## Full Government Application Form
Complete multi-page government application with conditional fields, file uploads, common fields, FOIP notice, and declaration checkbox

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "applicantName": {
      "$ref": "https://adsp.alberta.ca/common.v1.schema.json#/definitions/personFullName"
    },
    "email": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "email",
      "minLength": 1
    },
    "phone": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1
    },
    "mailingAddress": {
      "$ref": "https://adsp.alberta.ca/common.v1.schema.json#/definitions/postalAddressAlberta"
    },
    "applicationType": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "New Application",
        "Renewal",
        "Amendment"
      ]
    },
    "hasSupplementaryDocs": {
      "type": "boolean"
    },
    "supplementaryDocument": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "file-urn"
    },
    "additionalNotes": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "iDeclare": {
      "type": "boolean",
      "allOf": [
        {
          "enum": [
            true
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "email",
    "phone",
    "applicationType",
    "iDeclare"
  ],
  "if": {
    "properties": {
      "hasSupplementaryDocs": {
        "const": true
      }
    }
  },
  "then": {
    "required": [
      "supplementaryDocument"
    ]
  }
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "Categorization",
  "options": {
    "variant": "pages",
    "title": "Government Service Application",
    "subtitle": "Apply for the program"
  },
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "Category",
      "label": "Personal Information",
      "options": {
        "sectionTitle": "About You"
      },
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "HelpContent",
          "options": {
            "markdown": true,
            "help": [
              "Please provide your contact information. All fields marked with * are required."
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/applicantName"
        },
        {
          "type": "HorizontalLayout",
          "elements": [
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/email",
              "options": {
                "help": "We'll use this to send you updates on your application."
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "Control",
              "scope": "#/properties/phone",
              "options": {
                "help": "Include area code (e.g., 780-555-0123)."
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Category",
      "label": "Mailing Address",
      "options": {
        "sectionTitle": "About You"
      },
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/mailingAddress"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Category",
      "label": "Application Details",
      "options": {
        "sectionTitle": "Your Application"
      },
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/applicationType",
          "options": {
            "format": "radio"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/hasSupplementaryDocs",
          "label": "Do you have supplementary documents to upload?"
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/supplementaryDocument",
          "options": {
            "variant": "dragdrop"
          },
          "rule": {
            "effect": "SHOW",
            "condition": {
              "scope": "#/properties/hasSupplementaryDocs",
              "schema": {
                "const": true
              }
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/additionalNotes",
          "options": {
            "multi": true,
            "help": "Provide any additional information relevant to your application."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Category",
      "label": "Review & Submit",
      "options": {
        "sectionTitle": "Submission"
      },
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "HelpContent",
          "options": {
            "markdown": true,
            "help": [
              "#### Notice of Collection",
              "The personal information on this form is collected under the authority of Section 33(c) of the *Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act* (FOIP). If you have any questions contact us at [support@gov.ab.ca](mailto:support@gov.ab.ca)."
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/iDeclare",
          "options": {
            "text": "I declare that the information I have provided is true and correct to the best of my knowledge."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- This combines: multi-page stepper, common fields ($ref), conditional file upload, FOIP notice, and declaration
- Section titles group related categories (pages) on the task list
- The if/then conditional makes supplementaryDocument required only when hasSupplementaryDocs is true
- Always pair SHOW/HIDE rules with matching if/then conditional validation in the data schema
- Use schemaDefinitionTool to load common schema definitions before using $ref for fullName and address
- The FOIP notice and declaration checkbox are required on most Alberta government forms

## Contact/Feedback Form with Conditional Routing
Simple feedback form with category-based conditional fields and custom validation messages

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "fullName": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 1
    },
    "email": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "email",
      "minLength": 1
    },
    "category": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "General Inquiry",
        "Technical Issue",
        "Complaint",
        "Suggestion"
      ]
    },
    "urgency": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": [
        "Low",
        "Medium",
        "High",
        "Critical"
      ]
    },
    "issueDescription": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 10,
      "errorMessage": {
        "minLength": "Please provide at least 10 characters describing your issue."
      }
    },
    "stepsToReproduce": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "preferredResolution": {
      "type": "string"
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "fullName",
    "email",
    "category",
    "issueDescription"
  ],
  "allOf": [
    {
      "if": {
        "properties": {
          "category": {
            "const": "Technical Issue"
          }
        }
      },
      "then": {
        "required": [
          "stepsToReproduce"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "if": {
        "properties": {
          "category": {
            "const": "Complaint"
          }
        }
      },
      "then": {
        "required": [
          "urgency",
          "preferredResolution"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### UI schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "VerticalLayout",
  "elements": [
    {
      "type": "HelpContent",
      "options": {
        "markdown": true,
        "help": [
          "### Contact Us",
          "Please fill out the form below and we'll get back to you within 2 business days."
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "HorizontalLayout",
      "elements": [
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/fullName"
        },
        {
          "type": "Control",
          "scope": "#/properties/email"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/category",
      "options": {
        "format": "radio"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/urgency",
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/category",
          "schema": {
            "const": "Complaint"
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/issueDescription",
      "options": {
        "multi": true,
        "help": "Describe your inquiry in detail. Be specific about what happened."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/stepsToReproduce",
      "label": "Steps to reproduce the issue",
      "options": {
        "multi": true,
        "help": "List the steps someone would follow to encounter this issue."
      },
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/category",
          "schema": {
            "const": "Technical Issue"
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Control",
      "scope": "#/properties/preferredResolution",
      "options": {
        "multi": true,
        "help": "Tell us how you'd like this resolved."
      },
      "rule": {
        "effect": "SHOW",
        "condition": {
          "scope": "#/properties/category",
          "schema": {
            "const": "Complaint"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
\`\`\`

### Notes
- This demonstrates a single-page form with allOf conditional validation and category-based SHOW rules
- Each category shows different follow-up fields: Technical Issue → steps to reproduce, Complaint → urgency + resolution
- Custom errorMessage on issueDescription provides better guidance than default AJV messages
- Always pair SHOW rules with if/then conditional required in the data schema
- Uses HorizontalLayout for name/email on one row, radio buttons for category selection

## Vendor Registration with Repeating Items
Multi-page vendor registration form with repeating product list, data registers, and file upload

### Data schema
\`\`\`json
{
  "type": "object",
